One Command Line Plot - The Rest

Walter Xie

09/02/2017

Introduction

One of the feature of ComMA package is to simplify ggplot2 codes into one-line functions, and also to provide some other useful utility functions.

library(ComMA)
#getwd()

Box Whiskers plot

Load the example data model.test, and display the first 3 rows:

data(model.test)
model.test[1:3,]
##   model test performance  OS
## 1   GTR 1044    1.144838 Mac
## 2   GTR 1366    1.081676 Mac
## 3   GTR 1510    1.078596 Mac

Plot the performance score of each test in four GTR models, where the texts of x-axis were rotated, and also use verbose=F to block messages:

ggBoxWhiskersPlot(model.test, x.id="test", y.id="performance", colour.id="OS", x.text.angle=90, verbose = F)

Adjust view

Zoom the plot without change the underlying data

# Zoom the plot without change the underlying data
ggBoxWhiskersPlot(model.test, x.id="test", y.id="performance", colour.id="OS", 
                  x.text.angle=90, y.lim.cart=c(NA,5), verbose = F)

Use both bar.pos=“fill” and y.trans=“per” to create a typical percentage bar chart:

ggBoxWhiskersPlot(model.test, x.id="test", y.id="performance", colour.id="OS", 
                  x.text.angle=90, y.lim.cart=c(NA,5), verbose = F)

Histogram

This plots a 1d distribution by dividing “performance” into bins and counting the number of observations in each bin.

ggHistogram(model.test[model.test$performance<3,], x.id="performance", fill.id="model", 
            binwidth=0.1, x.text.angle=90, verbose=F)
